ce:section.ce:para:
Multi-color fluorescent CQDs were prepared through hydrothermal method. Critic acid (CA) and urea were mixed under vigorous stirring in varying ratio into different solvents (water, ethyl alcohol, and DMF) for 20 min. The solution in hydrothermal reactor was then heated at 160 °C/180 °C for 6 h/10 h, respectively (Table 1
                        ). After cooling down naturally to room temperature, the final CQDs solution was collected and named as X-CQDs (X = B, G, Y, O, R) solution. The schematic illustration of the synthesis process of CQDs is shown in Scheme 1
                        . CA and urea form nitrogen-rich CQDs with ample groups on the surfaces. During the hydrothermal process, different ratios of CA/urea, hydrothermal temperatures, reaction time, and solvents affect the generated CQDs, leading to the tunable emissions of CQDs.

Series of CQDs solution were synthesized with different reaction conditions. The ratio of CA/urea and solvents were adjusted to achieve multi-color emissions, and hydrothermal temperature and time were adjusted to obtain more intense emission properties. Finally, five CQDs solution samples were chosen as the representive samples for further investigation due to their appropriate colors of emission. The structural characterizations of CQDs were carried out by TEM, FTIR, and Raman spectra. The TEM images of CQDs are shown in Fig. 1
                         (a-e). The CQDs are almost monodispersed with an average diameter of about 3–4 nm with narrow size distribution. The CQDs with different emissions are in similar sizes, demonstrating that the tunable emission colors (as shown in Fig. 2
                        ) is not significantly related to the size effect of CQDs. The FTIR spectra are shown in Fig. 1(f). The CQDs possess abundant hydrophilic groups like stretching vibrations of C=C (1617 cm−1), C=N (1663 cm−1), C=O (1670 cm−1). Moreover, stretching vibrations of C-O-C (1254 cm−1), N-H (3206 cm−1), CH2 (2925 cm−1), and O-H (3424 cm−1) bonds are observed in each CQDs sample, which means polyaromatic structures are formed during the hydrothermal process [24–27]. The stretching vibrations for C=O bonds at 1670 cm−1 and C-O bonds at 1254 cm−1 increase from B-CQDs to R-CQDs, indicating that the increase of the CQDs surface oxidation probably results in the red shift of CQDs emission in Fig. 2(a). The CQDs samples show broad O-H bonds indicating that abundant hydroxyl groups grafting on the surface. The Raman spectra shown in Fig. 1(g) further confirm the formation of CQDs, the D-band at 1370 cm−1 is corresponding to the sp3 disordered carbon atom vibration, and the G-band at 1576 cm−1 proves the sp2 ordered graphite carbon [28].
